{
  "texts": [
    "Since the 1990s, cognitive science has increasingly embraced the '4E' paradigm.",
    "From work in bio-inspired robotics and approaches emphasising first-person human experience, 4E understands cognition as embodied, embedded, enactive, and extended (e.g., Brookes, 1991; Varela et al., 1991; Maturana & Varela, 1987; Hutchins, 1995; Clark 1997; Clark & Chalmers, 1998; Ward et al., 2017).",
    "Recently, the achievements Doi: 10.1098/rstb.2023.0148.R2 Philosophical Transactions Royal Society B 3 move it away from deleterious exchanges with the environment, bringing the system closer to those expected states conducive to survival.",
    "This, in turn, requires a method of efficient learning.",
    "Rather than passively waiting for incoming sensory information, systems are proactive, generating \"top-down\" predictions about future states (Hohwy, 2013; Clark, 2016)."
  ]
}